Close contact with a confirmed case means:
  • Face-to-face contact for longer than 10 minutes
  • Direct, physical contact (touching, shaking hands, kissing)

  • Contact with or exchange of body fluids

results.text:
Your Risk Score
Interpretation: %(v_score_interpretation)s

Your Risk Score is equal to the highest score in your Risk Profile. For your Risk Profile please see below.

Symptom Score
Exposition Score

Severe Illness Score
Dissemination Score


How is the risk profile generated?

Based on your responses CovApp has created a personal risk profile which is also used for your recommendations.

Your risk profile has four risk dimensions with a value between 0 and 100 points. While a lower score implies lower risk, higher scores indicate a higher risk. These scores are only intended to serve as a rough orientation without any guarantee.

These are the four risk dimensions:

1. Symptom Score: This score increases if your responses indicate symptoms that can be related to COVID-19.

2. Exposition Score: This score increases if you have encounters or circumstances, which imply that you could have been in contact with the novel coronavirus.

3. Severe Illness Score: This score increases if your responses indicate any circumstances (e.g. chronic diseases, medications, or similar) that increase your chance of severe illness if you are infected by the novel coronavirus.

4. Dissemination Score: This score increases, if you have a private or work-related environment that favors the spread of the virus if you are infected and infectious.

Symptom and Exposition Scores are used together with your vaccination status to compile the "Test Recommendation". The Severe COVID-19 Score is combined with your vaccination status for the "Recommendations for Severe COVID-19". The Dissemination Score is interpreted in combination with the probability of infection to create the "Recommendations to prevent spread of virus".

%(v_red)s Please self-isolate from other persons to prevent transmission of the virus and follow these rules:

1.) Please stay home except to get medical care. If you need to leave your home, avoid public transportation and wear a mask.
2.) Stay in a separate room and away from other people in your home.
3.) Notify close contacts that they may have been exposed to COVID-19. The novel coronavirus can spread 48 hours before you have developed symptoms or tested positive. By letting your friends and colleagues know, you can prevent further infections and help to protect everyone.
4.) Follow instructions from your healthcare provider and local health department.

For more information, take a look at the CDC guidelines.

results.text:
%(v_red)s Antiviral Therapy

Some users with your responses may benefit from an approved antiviral treatment for COVID-19 due to a higher risk of developing severe illness.

A call center is available at: 1-800-232-0233 to get help (in English and more than 150 languages) from 8:00 am to midnight ET, 7 days a week.
The Disability Information and Access Line (DIAL) is also available to specifically help people with disabilities access services. To get help, call 1-888-677-1199, Monday-Friday from 9:00 am to 8:00 pm ET or email DIAL@usaginganddisability.org.

To help find participating treatment sites closest to you, please click here.

%(v_red)s Get boosted.


Most users with your responses should get a booster shot.

  • Although vaccination prevents severe disease, the effectiveness at preventing infection or severe illness wanes over time.
  • A booster shot will give you additional protection against the highly transmissible omicron variant which is currently the cause for most infections in the US.
  • A booster shot increases the immune response against the novel coronavirus. With an increased immune response, individuals have improved protection against getting infected with the novel coronavirus and are less likely to develop severe disease.
  • A booster is recommended for individuals who were vaccinated with Pfizer-BioNTech or Moderna 6 months earlier or with the J&J/Janssen single-dose vaccine 2 months earlier.

Booster shots are free and available throughout the US.

For vaccination sites near you and to schedule an appointment click here or call 1-800-232-0233 .

For more information regarding boosters, please also visit CDC.
